{{sport-year-stub}}

The '''64th [[NHK Cup (shogi)|NHK Cup]]''', or as it is officially known the {{nihongo|'''64th NHK Cup TV Shogi Tournament'''|第64回NHK杯テレビ将棋トーナメント|dairokujūyonkai enueichikeihai terebi shōgi tōnamento}} was a professional [[shogi]] tournament organized by the [[Japan Shogi Association]] and sponsored by [[Japan|Japan's]] [[Public broadcasting#Japan|public broadcaster]] [[NHK]]. Play began on April 6, 2014 and ended on March 22, 2015. The 50-player single elimination tournament was won by [[Toshiyuki Moriuchi]]. All of the tournament games were shown on [[NHK-E]]. The {{nihongo|[[Sports commentator#Main/Play-by-play commentator|host]]|司会者|shikaisha}} during the NHK-E broadcasts was [[Professional shogi player#Female professionals|female professional]] [[Ichiyo Shimizu]].<ref name="64th NHK TV Shogi Tournament">{{cite web|url=http://cgi2.nhk.or.jp/goshogi/shogitou|title=Dai Rokujūyonkai NHK Shōgi Terebi Tōnamento|script-title=ja:第64回NHKテレビ将棋トーナメント|trans-title=64th NHK TV Shogi Tournament|language=Japanese|publisher=NHK|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610021348/http://cgi2.nhk.or.jp/goshogi/shogitou/|archivedate=June 10, 2014|access-date=December 22, 2017|df=}}</ref> {{TOC limit|2}}
== Participants == ===Preliminary tournaments=== A total of 128 [[Professional shogi players|shogi professionals]] competed in 18 preliminary tournaments to qualify for the main tournament. These tournaments were untelevised one-day tournaments held at the [[Japan Shogi Association#Headquarters and other offices|Tokyo Shogi Kaikan]] and [[Japan Shogi Association#Headquarters and other offices|Kansai Shogi Kaikan]]. Each tournament consisted of seven or eight players. The initial time control for each player was 20 minutes followed by a 30-second [[byo-yomi|''byōyomi'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shogi.or.jp/kisen/nhk/64/yosen.html|title=Dai Rokujūkai NHK Haisen Yosen|script-title=ja:第64回NHK杯戦予選|trans-title=64th NHK Cup preliminaries|language=ja|year=2014|publisher=[[Japan Shogi Association]]|access-date=May 30, 2014}}</ref>
The female professional seed was determined by a single-game playoff between [[Tomomi Kai]] 2-crown (Women's ōi and Kurashiki Tōka) and [[Manao Kagawa]] (Women's ōshō), which was won by Kagawa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cgi2.nhk.or.jp/goshogi/kifu/sgs.cgi?d=20140316|title=Dai Rokujūkai NHK Hai Shutsujō Joryūkishi Ketteisen|script-title=ja:2014年03月16日第64回NHK杯出場女流棋士決定戦|trans-title=March 16, 2014, 64th NHK Cup Women's Professional Playoff|language=ja|publisher=NHK|access-date=May 30, 2014}}</ref> Brackets from two of the preliminary tournaments are shown below. {| |- valign="top" |[[File:64th NHK CupTV Shogi Brackets Prelim7.svg|thumb|250px|7-player preliminary tournament won by Yasuaki Tsukuda 9d]] |[[File:64th NHK CupTV Shogi Brackets Prelim8.svg|thumb|250px|8-player preliminary tournament won by Hiroshi Kobayashi 7d]] |- |}
===Main tournament=== The first time control for main tournament games was ten minutes per player. Once this was used up, a second time control of 10 one-minute periods of {{nihongo|[[time control#Japanese byo-yomi|"thinking time"]]|考慮時間|kōryō jikan}} began. Each player was given 30 seconds to make their move. If they did so, then no thinking time periods were used. If, however, they did not, a thinking time period began and they then had up to one minute (more specifically 59 seconds) to make a move before entering the next thinking time period. This process was repeated until a player had used all ten thinking time periods when the final ''byōyomi'' time control of 30 seconds per move began.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cgi2.nhk.or.jp/goshogi/shogitou#main_bottom|title=Taikyoku no Rūru|script-title=ja:対局のルール|trans-title=Game rules|language=Japanese|publisher=NHK|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610021348/http://cgi2.nhk.or.jp/goshogi/shogitou/#main_bottom|archive-date=June 10, 2014|access-date=December 22, 2017|df=}}</ref> ''[[Shogi#Equipment|Sente]]'' was determined prior to each game by [[Shogi#Setup and gameplay|piece toss]].
The 50 players listed below qualified for the main tournament.
