===Semifinals=== The two remaining players from each block with paired against each other to determine the respective block winners. The 1st semifinal game between Kōichi Fukaura 9d (''sente'') and Toshiyuki Moriuchi 9d (''gote'') was broadcast on March 1, 2015. Moriuchi won the game in 166 moves to win block B. The guest analyst was Yaumitsu Satō 9d.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Dai Rokujūyonkai NHK Shōgi Terebi Tōnamento Junkesshō Dai Ikkyoku|script-title=ja:第64回NHK将棋テレビトーナメント準決勝第1局|language=ja|trans-title=64th NHK TV Shogi Tournament Semifinal Game 1|airdate= March 1, 2015|last1=Yauchi|first1=Rieko (host)|last2=Satō|first2=Yasumitsu (guest analyst)|network=NHK-E|series=64th NHK TV Shogi Tournament}}</ref> The 2nd semifinal game was between Hisashi Namekata 8d (''sente'') and Takanori Hashimoto 8d (''gote''). The game was broadcast on March 8, 2015 and won by Namekata 8d when Hashimoto 8d was disqualified for making an illegal move ([[Shogi#Drops|Nifu]]) on his 92nd move.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asahi.com/articles/ASH386RPRH38UCVL00P.html|title=Hashimoto Hachidan ga "Nifu", Irei no Hansokumake, Shogi no NHKhai|script-title=ja:橋本八段が｢二歩｣, 異例の反則負け 将棋のNHK杯|trans-title=Hashimoto 8d loss by disqualification an anomaly, plays the illegal move "Nifu" in the Shogi NHK Cup|date=March 8, 2015|website=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|language=ja |deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150308114630/http://www.asahi.com/articles/ASH386RPRH38UCVL00P.html|archive-date=March 8, 2015|access-date=March 8, 2015}}</ref> Namekata thus won block A and advanced to the finals of the tournament for the first time. The guest analyst for the 2nd semifinal game was Kazuki Kimura 8d. The host for both semifinal games was female professional [[Rieko Yauchi]] 5d.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Dai Rokujūyonkai NHK Shōgi Terebi Tōnamento Junkesshō Dai Nikyoku|script-title=ja:第64回NHK将棋テレビトーナメント準決勝第2局|language=Japanese|trans-title=64th NHK TV Shogi Tournament Semifinal Game 2|airdate= March 8, 2015|last1=Yauchi|first1=Rieko (host)|last2=Kimura|first2=Kazuki (guest analyst)|network=NHK-E|series=64th NHK TV Shogi Tournament}}</ref>
===Final=== After 109 preliminary tournament games and 58 main tournament games involving 161 players, Toshiyuki Moriuchi 9d and Hisashi Namekata 9d met in the final broadcast on March 22, 2015. This was the first NHK Cup final appearance for Namekata and the fifth appearance for Moriuchi. The piece toss before the game resulted in Namekata being sente. Moriuchi won the game in 134 moves, thus winning the tournament for the third time and becoming the 64th NHK Cup Champion. The guest analyst for the final match were Takeshi Fujii 9d and the hosts of the final were NHK announcer {{ill|Ryō Nagano|ja|長野亮}} and female professional Ichiyo Shimizu.
The game score and a diagram showing the final position is given below.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cgi2.nhk.or.jp/goshogi/kifu/sgs.cgi?d=20150322|script-title=ja:NHK杯テレビ将棋トーナメント棋譜, 2015年3月22日第64回NHK杯決勝|trans-title=NHK Cup TV Shogi Tournament game score, 64th NHK Cup Final (March 22, 2015)|title=NHKhai Terebi Shōgi Tōnamento Kifu, Nisenjūgonen Sangatsu Nijūninichi Dai Rokujūyonkai NHKhai Kesshō|language=ja|publisher=NHK|access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref>
