== Other == * In addition to the defending champion Gōda, there were nine other former champions who qualified for the main tournament: Habu (38th, 41st, 45th, 47th—48th, 50th, 58th—61st), Y. Satō (56th—57th), Moriuchi (46th, 51st), Suzuki (49th), Miura (52nd), Kubo (53rd), Yamasaki (54th), Maruyama (55th), Watanabe (62nd). * ''Sente'' won 29 (a little under 60%) of the 49 games. * The average number of moves for the main tournament games was 120. The most moves played in a single game was 252 (Rd. 2, Namekata vs. Sawada){{efn|The first game between the two ended in impasse and the second game won by Namekata lasted 88 moves, so it actually took 340 moves for a winner to be determined}} while the fewest number of moves played was 68 (Rd. 2, Miura vs. Toyoshima). * Namekata versus Sawada in round 2 ended in impasse and both players played a second game with sente-gote reversed to determine the final result.{{efn|The first game ended in impasse after 252 moves. Since both players had more than the required 24 points to establish impasse (Namekata had 25 points and Sawada had 29), Namekata proposed impasse and Sawada accepted. A second game at adjusted time controls was then played between the two which Namekata won in 88 moves.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Dai Rokujūyonkai NHK Shōgi Terebi Tōnamento Ikkaisen Daikyūkyoku|script-title=ja:第64回NHK将棋テレビトーナメント1回戦第9局|language=Japanese|trans-title=64th NHK TV Shogi Tournament Round 1 Game 9|airdate= June 1, 2014|last1=Shimizu|first1=Ichiyo (host)|last2=Morishita|first2=Taku (guest analyst)|network=[[NHK-E]]|series=64th NHK TV Shogi Tournament}}</ref>}} Satō versus Fujii in round 2 ended in sennichite after 70 moves. The game was replayed with Fujii being sente at adjusted time controls{{efn|Satō had one thinking-time period and Fujii had three-thinking time periods remaining when the first game ended. The time control for the replay game was 1 move per 30 seconds for each player with Fujii having seven thinking-time periods and Satō having only five.}} which Fujii won in 121 moves.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Dai Rokujūyonkai NHK Shōgi Terebi Tōnamento Nikaisen Daijūkyoku|script-title=ja:第64回NHK将棋テレビトーナメント2回戦第10局|language=Japanese|trans-title=64th NHK TV Shogi Tournament Round 2 Game 10|airdate= October 12, 2014|last1=Shimizu|first1=Ichiyo (host)|last2=Hirose|first2=Akihito (guest analyst)|network=[[NHK-E]]|series=64th NHK TV Shogi Tournament}}</ref> *There was one disqualification due to an illegal move:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shogi.or.jp/shogi/hon/05.html|title=5. Hansoku ni Tsuite|script-title=ja:5.反則について|trans-title=Rules violations|language=Japanese|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140708202140/http://www.shogi.or.jp/shogi/hon/05.html|archive-date=July 8, 2014|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref> Hashimoto 8d lost his semifinal game against Namekata 8d for the illegal move "Nifu" on his 92nd move. *The age breakdown (age at start of the tournament) for the players who qualified was as follows: 10–19 years old, 2 players; 20–29 years old, 15 players; 30–39 years old, 11 players; 40–49 years old, 18 players; 50–59 years old, 4 players. The oldest player was Kōji Tosa 7d (59 years old) and the youngest player was Yūki Sasaki 4d (19 years old).
